Title: The Rabbi Who Found Messiah

reviewText: What we may have here is a possible sensationalism of someone who spent 80 years of his life talking with spirits and using amulets during mystic Kaballah practices and then at the end purporting to have had a vision from the MOST HIGH G-D. I know my Bible pretty well and it just didn't set well with me. This book is a book for itching ears. I wasn't impressed. I don't know enough about Judaism or the mystical Kaballah to be a good judge but as I read some of this book I got more and more uncomfortable and as a result lost an entire nights sleep. I don't recommend it. This book should get 1* for the picture on the front and that's it! I found the author to be misrepresenting his education with only his word regarding his diplomas. Sounds a lot like O. Pass it by.
summary: Possibly a fraudulent message and vision
Title: The Rabbi Who Found Messiah

reviewText: A Baptist minister who is telling the story of this venerable (old and respected) Jewish Rabbi who at the very end of his life had some kind of an interaction with Jesus and left a note only to be opened a year after his death.  So the book is very respectful and seems trustworthy.
Title: The Rabbi Who Found Messiah

reviewText: This DVD is utter and complete nonsense. A Torah scholar as great as Rabbi Kaduri, would never, ever ever believe in something so obviously absurd as JESUS. To suggest otherwise is to be extremely disrespectful not only to Rabbi Kaduri, but to many thousands of years of traditional Judaism. Christians can't seem to accept the fact that we Jews know better than to believe in their ridiculously false beliefs about JESUS.
